Throwing exceptions.

To raise an exception explicitly, use the throw keyword. The expression after throw must be a Throwable instance, almost always one you construct with new. The Java standard library gives you several ready made unchecked exception types that cover most cases. Reach for Illegal Argument Exception when the caller passed a value outside what the method accepts. Reach for Illegal State Exception when the method is called on an object that is not in a state to handle the call. Reach for Null Pointer Exception when a required reference is null. There is a helper called Objects dot require Non Null that throws Null Pointer Exception with a clean message. Reach for Unsupported Operation Exception when the operation is not supported on this implementation, like calling add on an immutable list.
